### goodwork-workspace/eval/personas/p1-burnt-out-engineer.md
1:# Persona 1: Burnt-Out Engineer
3:## Hidden ground truth
5:- **Snapshot**: Maya Shah, 36, senior/staff backend engineer at a fintech. Employed, depleted, saying "I just need something different" while being best known for reliability rescues.
6:- **Energy map**: Energizers: building internal tools, simplifying gnarly systems, mentoring two engineers at a time, writing design docs that unblock people. Drainers: incident command, executive status updates, being the escalation point, vague cross-team alignment. Anti-spark: production reliability leadership. Flow: 2-3 hour quiet blocks, clear technical problem, fast user feedback from engineers.
7:- **Activities & interests**: Investigating, building/fixing, organizing technical knowledge. Persistent curiosities: developer experience, education for engineers, climate data infra, humane on-call design.
8:- **Strengths & proof**: Learns complex systems fast; turns chaos into simple diagrams and tools; trusted under pressure. Proof episodes: reduced deploy failures with a release checklist/tool; mentored a new hire into owning billing work; led a migration after two failed attempts. Overuse risk: becomes the cleanup crew.
9:- **Anchors & values**: Top values: autonomy, craft, calm/sustainability, usefulness, fair pay. Will trade some pay for lower interrupt load, but not below $180k. Says "maybe leadership" but actually avoids people-management politics.
10:- **Motivation conditions**: Needs method autonomy, protected focus time, direct feedback from tool users, manager who shields interrupts. A day feels wasted when it is all Slack triage.
11:- **Meaning & service**: Wants work that makes other builders better. Mission is a plus, not worth chronic stress. Ethical line: manipulative finance products.
12:- **Craft**: Still wants to refine system design, observability, and explaining complex systems clearly.
13:- **Market position**: Strong distributed systems/reliability capital, fintech credibility, internal-tool portfolio hidden inside company. Candidate-market hypotheses: developer productivity, platform enablement with sane on-call, technical education.
14:- **Constraints & risk budget**: Mortgage and one child; must keep health insurance; 6 months cash runway only if cutting expenses; remote or hybrid in Boston; comp floor $180k base.
15:- **Whole-life dashboard**: Health low from sleep disruption; love/play squeezed by weekend incident work.
16:- **Work orientation & weighting**: Career orientation, not calling. Feels-good 45, is-good 40, does-good 15 for this season.
